00:25:25,460 --> 00:25:28,922
Several times, sir.
l spoke to a Mr Shipler.

241
00:25:28,962 --> 00:25:30,256
And?

242
00:25:30,297 --> 00:25:33,509
Senator, all they seem to know
is that my son is missing.

243
00:25:33,551 --> 00:25:37,763
Hm. Have you been
to the State Department?

244
00:25:37,803 --> 00:25:42,142
l have tried, sir, many different people.
You are the first that would see me.

245
00:25:42,183 --> 00:25:45,102
Well, l urge you to get to them, Mr Horman.

246
00:25:46,144 --> 00:25:48,564
l'm tying, sir.

247
00:25:50,190 --> 00:25:52,651
How does your son make a living?

248
00:25:52,691 --> 00:25:54,944
Well, frankly, l...

249
00:25:56,195 --> 00:26:00,116
l guess he's a writer.
Well, he says that he wants to...

250
00:26:01,241 --> 00:26:03,744
The important thing right now is to help him.

251
00:26:04,578 --> 00:26:06,413
Yes, sir.

252
00:26:06,454 --> 00:26:08,539
Here in the State Department, sir,

253
00:26:08,580 --> 00:26:14,044
we've investigated and have been unable
to find any trace of your son.

254
00:26:14,085 --> 00:26:18,465
Neither our embassy nor the militay
government knows where he is.

255
00:26:18,505 --> 00:26:21,092
The New York Times says he was arrested.

256
00:26:21,133 --> 00:26:24,345
That's what your daughter-in-law
told the press.

257
00:26:24,387 --> 00:26:26,263
She...

258
00:26:26,304 --> 00:26:30,600
She's been pestering
those embassy people, so they told me.

259
00:26:34,644 --> 00:26:40,067
Tery Simon is a friend. She was there
on vacation, caught in the coup.

260
00:26:40,108 --> 00:26:42,235
She confirmed everrything Beth told me.

261
00:26:42,276 --> 00:26:46,698
The arrested Americans have all been
released thanks to our embassy's efforts.

262
00:26:46,739 --> 00:26:49,867
The last two, Teruggi and Holloway...

263
00:26:49,909 --> 00:26:51,869
They're friends of your son's.

264
00:26:51,909 --> 00:26:55,872
..were released, and Teruggi left
without even thanking the embassy.

265
00:26:55,914 --> 00:26:59,375
Mr Horman, this is gonna take a little time.

266
00:26:59,416 --> 00:27:04,838
l suggest you go back up to New York
and relax and let us handle it.

267
00:27:06,172 --> 00:27:09,968
l met him in New York
at the Third Church of Christ Scientist.

268
00:27:10,010 --> 00:27:14,180
- Doubt he'd remember.
- You're a Christian Scientist too?

269
00:27:14,222 --> 00:27:15,681
And your son?

270
00:27:15,723 --> 00:27:19,518
- You know how young people are.
- Of course.

271
00:27:19,559 --> 00:27:22,187
Mr Horman, would you mind
waiting here a moment?

272
00:27:22,229 --> 00:27:24,314
No, not at all.

273
00:27:38,742 --> 00:27:40,828
- Mr Horman?
- Yes.

274
00:27:40,869 --> 00:27:43,455
- l think we've met before.
- Yes, Congressman.

275
00:27:43,496 --> 00:27:45,707
New York? This is my assistant, Ann.

276
00:27:45,749 --> 00:27:47,834
- How do you do?
- You know Bob.

277
00:27:47,875 --> 00:27:50,211
Do you mind if we talk while walking?

278
00:27:50,252 --> 00:27:52,338
No. Not at all, sir.

279
00:27:53,839 --> 00:27:56,967
- What did they say?
- They think he's in hiding.

280
00:27:57,008 --> 00:27:59,761
- Why?
- Political reasons.

281
00:27:59,803 --> 00:28:02,388
They think he'll surface
when things calm down.

282
00:28:02,430 --> 00:28:06,726
- What are his politics?
- Liberal, l suppose.

283
00:28:06,767 --> 00:28:09,228
Liberal, or radical?

284
00:28:09,268 --> 00:28:13,607
Congressman, my son
is much too wishy-washy to be a radical.

285
00:28:13,648 --> 00:28:16,943
- Are you sure?
- What difference does it make?

286
00:28:16,984 --> 00:28:22,072
Well, it doesn't but you said
that Percy and Abzug are sending cables?

287
00:28:22,113 --> 00:28:24,991
They promised to,
but so did Kemp and Koch

288
00:28:25,033 --> 00:28:28,286
and Magnuson and Javits and you.

289
00:28:28,327 --> 00:28:30,830
Well, l'm certainly gonna consider it.

290
00:28:30,871 --> 00:28:32,957
Good luck. God bless.

291
00:28:33,748 --> 00:28:35,834
Nice meeting you, Mr Horman.

292
00:28:36,459 --> 00:28:38,336
Mr Horman.

293
00:29:14,700 --> 00:29:16,786
What's that? That.

294
00:29:18,288 --> 00:29:19,956
This?

295
00:29:19,998 --> 00:29:21,916
Those are my books.

296
00:29:21,957 --> 00:29:25,544
One of those is a Bible.
l'm a Christian Scientist.

297
00:29:25,586 --> 00:29:27,671
Pasaporte.

298
00:29:32,716 --> 00:29:36,429
Mr Horman? l'm Phil Putnam.
l'm the US Consul down here.

299
00:29:36,470 --> 00:29:39,098
- Thank heaven.
- Sorry about the confusion.

300
00:29:39,139 --> 00:29:41,725
That's all right. Is there any more news?

301
00:29:41,765 --> 00:29:46,020
Nothing so far, but l think
we're on top of the situation.

302
00:29:46,062 --> 00:29:48,731
Washington cabled us you were coming.

303
00:29:48,773 --> 00:29:53,485
;Déjenme, yo tengo
mi salvoconducto, déjenme!

304
00:29:53,526 --> 00:29:55,612
We're over here in the Ford.

305
00:29:56,821 --> 00:30:00,074
- You'd think there was a war on.
- There is, sort of.

306
00:30:00,115 --> 00:30:05,204
- l thought the coup was over.
- It is, but there are still problems.

307
00:30:05,244 --> 00:30:08,581
The ambassador can see you at 3:30
if that's OK.

308
00:30:08,622 --> 00:30:10,917
- The sooner the better.
- Good.

309
00:30:12,668 --> 00:30:16,797
- Cheerful little county you picked to live in.

310
00:30:16,839 --> 00:30:19,174
Yeah, well...

311
00:30:19,216 --> 00:30:21,301
How long have you been here?

312
00:30:21,343 --> 00:30:24,554
Three years, four months and 19 days.

313
00:30:24,594 --> 00:30:26,264
Counting the days.

314
00:30:26,305 --> 00:30:29,892
lt's not a bad county, really.
l'm just ready for a change.

315
00:30:29,933 --> 00:30:31,852
Where will you go next?

316
00:30:31,892 --> 00:30:34,396
My dream is to be posted to Brazil.

317
00:30:34,436 --> 00:30:38,649
But l'll go wherever they send me.
Al hotel Cabrera.

318
00:30:44,904 --> 00:30:46,781
Ed. Ed.

319
00:30:49,701 --> 00:30:53,746
l'm sorry l didn't meet you.
l've been tying to meet this Major Pieto...

320
00:30:53,786 --> 00:30:56,790
Mrs Horman? Hi. How are ya? You all right?

321
00:30:56,831 --> 00:30:58,625
All right.

322
00:30:58,666 --> 00:31:02,920
Good, good. Listen, we'll be back
to pick you folks up at 2:30.

323
00:31:02,962 --> 00:31:04,630
Yes, 2:30. That's fine.

324
00:31:04,671 --> 00:31:07,466
l've been tying to meet this Major Pieto.

325
00:31:07,508 --> 00:31:11,386
This morning was the only time
that l could meet him.

326
00:31:15,680 --> 00:31:18,768
And the bathroom, sir.
Thank you verry much.

327
00:31:28,191 --> 00:31:31,529
- How was your trip?
- A total delight.

328
00:31:37,574 --> 00:31:39,661
How's Elizabeth?

329
00:31:43,329 --> 00:31:45,416
How do you suppose?

330
00:31:50,586 --> 00:31:52,672
You blame me?

331
00:32:09,020 --> 00:32:11,814
Did you find out anything in Washington?

332
00:32:11,855 --> 00:32:13,940
No, but...

333
00:32:14,733 --> 00:32:18,319
Putnam thinks that things down here
are in good hands.

334
00:32:18,361 --> 00:32:21,739
- You don't agree?

335
00:32:21,781 --> 00:32:25,159
Well, l don't expect
a whole hell of a lot any more.

336
00:32:25,992 --> 00:32:28,078
No?

337
00:32:29,661 --> 00:32:31,998
Why?

338
00:32:32,038 --> 00:32:34,375
He's been gone two weeks.

339
00:32:34,416 --> 00:32:38,545
l don't know. They give me the same
song and dance over and over again.

340
00:32:41,506 --> 00:32:43,591
He could be hurt or...

341
00:32:44,676 --> 00:32:47,553
tortured.
They don't give a goddamn about him.

342
00:32:47,595 --> 00:32:51,848
l don't want to hear
any of your anti-Establishment paranoia!

343
00:32:53,225 --> 00:32:56,227
l certainly get enough of that from my son.

344
00:32:58,980 --> 00:33:03,984
lf he had settled down where he belongs,
this never would have happened.

345
00:33:07,320 --> 00:33:09,781
Please don't cy.

346
00:33:20,832 --> 00:33:22,458
Beth, l'll find him.

347
00:33:28,964 --> 00:33:32,759
Charles wrote that these toilet articles
were hard to get.

348
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:34,886
Not any more.

349
00:33:36,970 --> 00:33:39,056
His mother sent him fudge.

350
00:33:46,854 --> 00:33:49,190
Why don't you go freshen up?

351
00:33:49,231 --> 00:33:51,317
We only have one hour.

352
00:33:58,656 --> 00:34:01,242
Oh, by the way, where's Tery?

353
00:34:01,284 --> 00:34:03,369
At Braniff, picking up her ticket.

354
00:34:03,411 --> 00:34:05,621
- When does she go?
- Tomorrow.

355
00:34:05,663 --> 00:34:07,998
ls she all right?

356
00:34:08,040 --> 00:34:10,333
Yeah, Ed. So am l.

357
00:34:51,493 --> 00:34:54,288
- Come in.

358
00:35:06,339 --> 00:35:08,384
Ta-daa.

359
00:35:10,677 --> 00:35:13,054
Beth, l have to ask you a question.

360
00:35:13,095 --> 00:35:16,891
l want you to answer me
absolutely honestly.

361
00:35:16,933 --> 00:35:19,143
- OK.
- What did he do?

362
00:35:19,185 --> 00:35:22,146
- What?
- What stupid thing did Charles do

363
00:35:22,186 --> 00:35:25,190
to cause his arrest,
or make him go into hiding?

364
00:35:25,232 --> 00:35:29,027
- Ed, Charlie is not a stupid man.
- He wasn't too smart!

365
00:35:29,068 --> 00:35:34,323
l can tell you, getting in such a mess
that l have to fly 16 hours in order to...

366
00:35:36,532 --> 00:35:40,537
Sometimes l honestly think that that boy
is incapable of doing anything,

367
00:35:40,578 --> 00:35:46,083
except give idealistic speeches
and write novels that'll never be published.

368
00:35:46,124 --> 00:35:49,086
Unless the disappearing act is a stunt

369
00:35:49,126 --> 00:35:53,340
- to publicise his autobiography.
- Why don't you just go home?

370
00:35:53,380 --> 00:35:55,508
l'll find my husband by myself.

371
00:35:55,550 --> 00:35:58,969
- l'll be ready in a few minutes.
- Take your time.

372
00:35:59,010 --> 00:36:01,764
l still want an answer to that question.

373
00:36:16,776 --> 00:36:19,863
- Mr Ambassador, Mr Horman.
- Come right in, sir.

374
00:36:19,903 --> 00:36:21,781
- My pleasure.
- Mine too.

375
00:36:21,823 --> 00:36:25,618
Captain Tower, US Navy,
our senior militay group officer.

376
00:36:25,658 --> 00:36:28,161
Colonel Clay, our defence attaché.

377
00:36:28,202 --> 00:36:30,872
- Mr Horman.
- Thank you.

378
00:36:31,955 --> 00:36:34,125
Mrs Horman, how are you today?

379
00:36:34,167 --> 00:36:35,835
Fine.

380
00:36:36,919 --> 00:36:39,380
- Shall l review?
- Yes. But first...

381
00:36:39,421 --> 00:36:44,009
l want to express our deep concern
over your son's disappearance.

382
00:36:44,050 --> 00:36:45,969
- Thank you.
- l assure you

383
00:36:46,009 --> 00:36:49,930
everry element at our disposal
has been and will continue to be utilised

384
00:36:49,972 --> 00:36:51,974
to facilitate his safe return.

385
00:36:52,016 --> 00:36:56,019
That's exactly what l'd hoped to hear,
Mr Ambassador.

386
00:36:56,061 --> 00:36:57,979
Go ahead, Consul Putnam.

387
00:36:58,020 --> 00:37:01,065
Sir, we've conducted
an extensive investigation.

388
00:37:01,106 --> 00:37:04,193
Captain Tower's staff
have interviewed residents

389
00:37:04,233 --> 00:37:06,903
in the area where Charles was last seen.

390
00:37:06,945 --> 00:37:12,617
Colonel Clay has maintained his contacts
with militay and police authorities.

391
00:37:12,657 --> 00:37:16,954
But after analysing all the data,
we still come to the conclusion

392
00:37:16,996 --> 00:37:20,374
- that he must be in hiding.
- From what?

393
00:37:20,414 --> 00:37:23,960
That's a valid question,
and one we'd like the answer to.

394
00:37:24,001 --> 00:37:26,837
We've been through this a hundred times.

395
00:37:26,879 --> 00:37:31,550
He's not hiding. Our whole neighbourhood
saw him picked up by a goon squad.

396
00:37:31,592 --> 00:37:34,135
The militay swears they haven't got him.

397
00:37:34,177 --> 00:37:38,848
l've been to the carabinero stations,
to the department of investigations,

398
00:37:38,890 --> 00:37:43,977
l even got into the national stadium,
and he's just not in their custody.

399
00:37:44,019 --> 00:37:48,356
So the hiding theoy seems to be
the most viable, at least for the present.

400
00:37:48,397 --> 00:37:52,610
That's dumb. If he were in hiding,
he'd let me know he was all right.

401
00:37:52,651 --> 00:37:57,155
Maybe he can't. There have been
a lot of civilian accidents and injuries.

402
00:37:57,197 --> 00:37:58,907
No shit, Sherlock.

403
00:38:02,452 --> 00:38:05,204
Were you going to say something,
Mr Horman?

404
00:38:05,245 --> 00:38:07,957
Er, yes. Er...

405
00:38:07,998 --> 00:38:11,334
As the colonel suggested,
if Charles was possibly injured,

406
00:38:11,375 --> 00:38:14,754
he could be in a coma,
or suffering from amnesia...

407
00:38:14,796 --> 00:38:16,672
Have you checked the hospitals?

408
00:38:16,713 --> 00:38:19,050
- Some.
- Not all?

409
00:38:19,091 --> 00:38:22,886
lt's pretty difficult to get into some hospitals
right now, and...

410
00:38:22,927 --> 00:38:27,098
Translated, he means you can break a leg
tripping over bodies.

411
00:38:28,598 --> 00:38:31,811
The only thing that we know
for sure right now

412
00:38:31,851 --> 00:38:34,146
is where he isn't.

413
00:38:34,188 --> 00:38:37,315
l may have some further news for you
after tonight.

414
00:38:37,357 --> 00:38:41,652
l'm having dinner with the junta's
chief of staff, Admiral Huidobro.

415
00:38:41,693 --> 00:38:46,323
God. That one again?
Haven't you seen him yet?

416
00:38:46,364 --> 00:38:48,617
These people are verry busy.

417
00:38:49,159 --> 00:38:51,077
l bet they are.

418
00:38:51,994 --> 00:38:54,038
By the way, Beth, do you have that list?

419
00:38:54,079 --> 00:38:56,332
What list?

420
00:38:56,373 --> 00:39:00,878
l asked her for a list of Charles' friends
so l could extend this investigation.

421
00:39:02,086 --> 00:39:04,172
l'll see that you get it.

422
00:39:05,507 --> 00:39:09,552
You said several of Charles' friends
were contacted by the militay

423
00:39:09,593 --> 00:39:13,555
- after he was supposedly arrested.
- They all called the consulate.

424
00:39:13,596 --> 00:39:15,974
- What calls?
- l wasn't aware of any.

425
00:39:16,015 --> 00:39:18,309
You certainly were.

426
00:39:18,351 --> 00:39:23,230
l saw all the notes on the calls the day
Shipler showed me your file cards.

427
00:39:23,271 --> 00:39:27,192
l forgot that, sir. You're right.
Yes, l think l do remember.

428
00:39:28,150 --> 00:39:32,488
Why don't you check that out sometime
in the next couple of days?

429
00:39:32,530 --> 00:39:35,074
We'll meet again
to take stock of the situation.

430
00:39:35,990 --> 00:39:39,119
lf you need anything...
Dave? Driver, please.

431
00:39:39,161 --> 00:39:43,248
lf you need anything, let me or Captain
Tower know, and we'll arrange it.

432
00:39:43,288 --> 00:39:46,542
- l'll see that he gets that list.
- Not from me, he won't.

433
00:39:46,584 --> 00:39:50,296
l'll check the phone logs
and start working on the hospitals.

434
00:39:50,337 --> 00:39:52,714
- Thank you, Consul.
- Call me Phil.

435
00:39:52,756 --> 00:39:55,133
- Mrs Horman.
- Thank you again.

436
00:39:55,174 --> 00:39:57,885
What is the matter?
Why were you so rude?

437
00:39:57,927 --> 00:40:00,888
- Jesus Christ!
- And do you swear all the time?

438
00:40:00,929 --> 00:40:03,098
l'm sorry. l don't mean to offend you.

439
00:40:03,140 --> 00:40:05,225
Why aren't you cooperating with them?

440
00:40:05,267 --> 00:40:07,352
- l am cooperating.
- Oh...

441
00:40:07,394 --> 00:40:10,063
l've been cooperating for two weeks, Ed!

442
00:40:10,104 --> 00:40:13,983
l'm sick and tired of getting fucked around
by these people, that's why!

443
00:40:14,023 --> 00:40:15,943
- To the hotel, sir?
- Yes.

444
00:40:21,072 --> 00:40:23,366
- Want some?
- Uh-uh.

445
00:40:24,783 --> 00:40:26,660
Back.

446
00:40:31,832 --> 00:40:33,708
Back.

447
00:40:36,127 --> 00:40:38,129
One more step.

448
00:40:41,631 --> 00:40:44,926
lt's an old joke.

449
00:40:44,968 --> 00:40:48,263
- We better go. Last bus is at six.
- Right.

450
00:40:48,303 --> 00:40:50,306
;Vámonos!

451
00:40:50,347 --> 00:40:52,725
- Catch!
- Right. l'll race ya.

452
00:40:52,766 --> 00:40:55,102
- Oh, no. No, you won't!
- l'll beat ya!

453
00:40:56,268 --> 00:41:00,565
Hay huelga de camioneros
y están bloqueados todos los caminos.

454
00:41:00,607 --> 00:41:03,568
- Sí, gracias. Fucking great.
- What?

455
00:41:03,609 --> 00:41:07,029
The truckers are on strike,
roads are all blocked.

456
00:41:07,070 --> 00:41:09,614
- How do we get back?
- We don't.

457
00:41:09,655 --> 00:41:11,741
Beth is gonna go nuts.

458
00:41:12,366 --> 00:41:14,994
lsn't there another way? Any trains?

459
00:41:15,035 --> 00:41:16,912
Mañana, a las 9.

460
00:41:16,953 --> 00:41:19,540
- What'd he say?
- He said, with luck,

461
00:41:19,580 --> 00:41:22,334
there might be a train tomorrow at nine.

462
00:41:23,792 --> 00:41:26,129
So what do we do till then?

463
00:41:30,883 --> 00:41:32,968
- What is it?
- l don't know.

464
00:41:58,949 --> 00:42:01,409
'That's the morning the coup started?'

465
00:42:01,450 --> 00:42:04,579
The 24-hour curfew
had shut everrything down.

466
00:42:04,621 --> 00:42:08,624
The phones were out. Charlie freaked
because he couldn't reach Beth.

467
00:42:08,665 --> 00:42:11,335
Did you pick that up from Charlie?

468
00:42:11,376 --> 00:42:15,547
Charles picked it up from me.
What happened next?

469
00:42:15,588 --> 00:42:18,966
Well, we stayed at the hotel.
We didn't have much choice.

470
00:42:19,007 --> 00:42:21,677
That's when you met all the Americans?

471
00:42:21,718 --> 00:42:24,471
And they were caught up
by the coup also?

472
00:42:25,972 --> 00:42:28,558
- The others.
- Then you met Babcock?

473
00:42:28,600 --> 00:42:33,187
No. Him we met the next morning.
Wednesday, September 12.

474
00:42:33,228 --> 00:42:35,314
- Here?
- Yeah, sure.

475
00:42:35,356 --> 00:42:38,567
Me permite su periódico, señor.

476
00:42:40,277 --> 00:42:43,321
You would do better to ask in English,
monsieur.

477
00:42:43,363 --> 00:42:46,282
- Tu es français? Pardon.
- English.

478
00:42:46,324 --> 00:42:49,410
l come from Paris, Texas, boy.

479
00:42:49,451 --> 00:42:52,162
- You're American.
- Red, white and blue.

480
00:42:52,204 --> 00:42:54,748
- Well, you fooled me.
- Good, good.

481
00:42:54,789 --> 00:42:57,667
l was just pulling your leg there...

482
00:42:57,707 --> 00:42:59,460
Charlie Horman.

483
00:42:59,502 --> 00:43:02,504
Nice to meet you.
This is my friend, Tery Simon.

484
00:43:02,546 --> 00:43:04,297
- How are you?
- All right.

485
00:43:04,338 --> 00:43:06,633
Yes, you are.

486
00:43:06,675 --> 00:43:09,010
Erm... That's my friend.

487
00:43:09,051 --> 00:43:11,137
- Hello.
- Hello.

488
00:43:11,177 --> 00:43:13,639
- Do you mind?
- No, help yourself.

489
00:43:13,680 --> 00:43:16,475
- What'd you say your name was?
- l didn't.

490
00:43:16,515 --> 00:43:19,769
- My name's Andrew Babcock.
- Nice to meet you.

491
00:43:19,811 --> 00:43:23,523
- Thanks a lot. Are you a tourist?
- No, not exactly.

492
00:43:23,564 --> 00:43:25,649
What are you doing down here?

493
00:43:25,690 --> 00:43:29,736
The navy sent me down here to do a job
and, er...she's done.

494
00:43:32,112 --> 00:43:33,948
Where are you stationed?

495
00:43:33,990 --> 00:43:37,576
Panama's my home base,
if that's what you mean.

496
00:43:37,618 --> 00:43:39,870
You said you're with the navy.

497
00:43:39,911 --> 00:43:42,831
l'm retired. l'm on a special assignment.

498
00:43:42,872 --> 00:43:45,417
Really? What's it like in Panama?

499
00:43:45,458 --> 00:43:48,544
- Panama's nice.
- Is it?

500
00:43:48,586 --> 00:43:53,340
And it's a good place
to keep an eye on everrything.

501
00:43:59,804 --> 00:44:02,139
There's my man from Milgroup.

502
00:44:03,516 --> 00:44:07,311
- What's Milgroup?
- Just a US militay group.

503
00:44:08,936 --> 00:44:11,940
There isn't
much news in there

504
00:44:11,981 --> 00:44:14,942
for someone with such big ears
and such a long nose.

505
00:44:15,484 --> 00:44:17,695
- But enjoy it.
- l will.

506
00:44:18,361 --> 00:44:20,447
- Enjoy.
- Thanks.

507
00:44:20,988 --> 00:44:22,866
Sure enough.

508
00:44:25,993 --> 00:44:29,205
'Charlie said, ''That's incredible.'''

509
00:44:29,246 --> 00:44:32,457
l can't believe he told us all that.

510
00:44:32,498 --> 00:44:35,543
That's when he decided
we should take notes.

511
00:44:35,584 --> 00:44:39,172
- Notes on what?
- Didn't you hear what she said?

512
00:44:39,212 --> 00:44:44,343
Ed, all those American officials
in Viña were probably involved in the coup.

513
00:44:44,383 --> 00:44:48,471
- Do you believe that, Tery?
- Why don't you believe me?

514
00:44:48,513 --> 00:44:51,891
You married Charles.
It colours your perceptions.

515
00:44:51,933 --> 00:44:55,936
- You're his damn father. What about yours?
- Come on.

516
00:44:55,977 --> 00:44:58,814
God! Whose side are you on?

517
00:45:02,107 --> 00:45:05,194
- How did you finally...

518
00:45:08,697 --> 00:45:10,240
How did you finally get home?

519
00:45:10,282 --> 00:45:12,576
'Ray Tower drove us back.

520
00:45:14,994 --> 00:45:16,829
Erm...

521
00:45:16,870 --> 00:45:18,914
That's all right. Listen...

522
00:45:18,955 --> 00:45:20,958
if you need anything, call me.

523
00:45:20,999 --> 00:45:23,919
Here's my business card.
My home number's on the back.

524
00:45:23,961 --> 00:45:25,087
OK.

525
00:45:25,127 --> 00:45:27,756
Guess who's having dinner again tonight?

526
00:45:27,796 --> 00:45:31,342
- Admiral Huidobro?
- Uh-huh.

527
00:45:31,841 --> 00:45:34,011
You gotta be kidding me. Again?

528
00:45:34,052 --> 00:45:38,848
- Again. Can you believe that guy?
- Did he ask for the list? Of course.

529
00:45:38,890 --> 00:45:41,851
ls this Tower?
How do you know him so well?

530
00:45:41,892 --> 00:45:44,145
We don't know him so well.

531
00:45:44,186 --> 00:45:47,356
When Charlie disappeared,
that's who we contacted.

532
00:45:47,398 --> 00:45:49,691
- He invited us for dinner.

533
00:45:49,732 --> 00:45:52,485
- He said Admiral...
- Huidobro.

534
00:45:52,527 --> 00:45:55,154
..Huidobro would be there and we could talk.

535
00:45:55,196 --> 00:45:59,408
- But this admiral never showed up.

536
00:46:07,665 --> 00:46:10,334
Ed, it happened just like this!

537
00:46:28,641 --> 00:46:32,562
You went to Tower's house
to see that admiral, and...

538
00:46:32,604 --> 00:46:34,939
This admiral never showed up.

539
00:46:34,980 --> 00:46:40,569
lt was past curfew, Tower insisted
we spend the night and we had to.

540
00:46:40,611 --> 00:46:43,405
- Tery?

541
00:46:50,118 --> 00:46:53,789
- What do you want?
- Got everrything you need?

542
00:46:53,829 --> 00:46:55,290
Yes.

543
00:46:56,166 --> 00:46:58,251
l appreciate everrything you've done

544
00:46:58,293 --> 00:47:02,004
but would you do me a favour
and get out of here? Please?

545
00:47:03,839 --> 00:47:05,924
You know, if l were you...

546
00:47:08,635 --> 00:47:10,720
l'd quit living in the past.

547
00:47:11,888 --> 00:47:16,183
l think it's about time
you started thinking about your future.

548
00:47:23,480 --> 00:47:27,068
You gotta learn to stay ahead
of the power curve, kid.

549
00:47:27,108 --> 00:47:29,945
- You know what l mean?
- Leave me alone!

550
00:47:29,987 --> 00:47:33,990
- Tery, it's me.
- It's an old aircraft carrier term.

551
00:47:34,031 --> 00:47:35,909
Come on. Hury up.

552
00:47:35,949 --> 00:47:39,495
lf a pilot gets ahead of the power curve
and something happens,

553
00:47:39,536 --> 00:47:42,081
- then he can pull up and away.
- Hury up!

554
00:47:42,122 --> 00:47:46,293
But if he falls behind the power curve
and something happens,

555
00:47:46,333 --> 00:47:50,797
then it's adios. You gotta stay ahead
of the power curve, kid.

556
00:47:54,466 --> 00:47:59,054
And when we woke up
the next morning, Tower was gone.

557
00:48:00,138 --> 00:48:02,223
- When does your plane leave?
- Nine.

558
00:48:02,265 --> 00:48:04,475
Would you take a letter for Elizabeth?

559
00:48:04,517 --> 00:48:06,894
- l'll see you in the morning.
- Good night.

560
00:48:06,936 --> 00:48:09,438
- Night, Ed.
- Want some fudge?

561
00:48:15,401 --> 00:48:17,987
Why did you take a bath in his house?

562
00:48:18,736 --> 00:48:20,823
Ed, l took a bath.

563
00:48:21,864 --> 00:48:23,950
We were stuck there.

564
00:48:32,958 --> 00:48:34,418
Ed?

565
00:48:35,168 --> 00:48:36,628
Ed.

566
00:48:37,461 --> 00:48:40,673
Wait a minute. Where are you going?

567
00:48:40,714 --> 00:48:43,467
Can't you lower your voice? For a walk.

568
00:48:43,509 --> 00:48:47,971
You can't go out for a walk.
It's curfew. You'll get shot.

569
00:48:57,270 --> 00:48:59,857
Did she have an affair with Charles?

570
00:49:02,734 --> 00:49:04,819
Why did you come here?

571
00:49:10,448 --> 00:49:15,162
'Había 4 soldados con un oficial
y dos más trayendo unas cajas.'

572
00:49:15,203 --> 00:49:17,956
'She says it was late afternoon.

573
00:49:17,997 --> 00:49:23,877
'There were four soldiers and an officer,
and two soldiers carried boxes of things.'

574
00:49:27,756 --> 00:49:30,008
Había otros soldados?

575
00:49:30,048 --> 00:49:33,636
Sí, había muchos,
esperando en un camión militar.

576
00:49:33,678 --> 00:49:37,389
There were many other soldiers
waiting in an army truck.

577
00:49:37,430 --> 00:49:40,350
'Qué estás diciendo, mujer?
No fue así, te equivocas.

578
00:49:40,392 --> 00:49:43,853
'Yo no oí más que unos pocos milicos
y era un auto particular.'

579
00:49:43,895 --> 00:49:46,897
'What did he say?'
'lt was a civilian truck,

580
00:49:46,938 --> 00:49:49,024
'and there weren't many soldiers.

581
00:49:49,066 --> 00:49:55,363
No, estoy segura, había muchos soldados
en un camión del ejército, yo los vi.'

582
00:49:55,405 --> 00:50:00,951
'She says there were many soldiers,
and it was definitely an army truck.'

583
00:50:01,534 --> 00:50:03,620
ls she sure it was Charles?

584
00:50:03,662 --> 00:50:06,623
Seguro que el muchacho fue mi marido?

585
00:50:06,664 --> 00:50:09,292
- Estoy segura que sí.
- Huh?

586
00:50:09,333 --> 00:50:12,003
- She's pretty sure.
- She's pretty sure?

587
00:50:12,044 --> 00:50:17,382
With witnesses like this, no wonder
nobody can find him. Buenos... Gracias.

588
00:50:17,424 --> 00:50:19,926
- Gracias.
- Hasta luego.

589
00:50:23,096 --> 00:50:27,558
- Is this the way you found it?
- No. It was a real shambles.

590
00:50:30,852 --> 00:50:33,229
- You were living here?
- Yeah.

591
00:50:36,314 --> 00:50:38,401
Why?

592
00:50:39,400 --> 00:50:41,487
We lived like everrybody else.

593
00:50:41,527 --> 00:50:46,658
l guess it's easy to be poor when you have
a round-trip ticket in your pocket.

594
00:50:46,698 --> 00:50:49,452
Let me explain something, Ed.

595
00:50:49,492 --> 00:50:54,123
We're here because we wanna be here.
We like it.

596
00:50:54,163 --> 00:50:57,417
We have friends here.
We're not playing poor.

597
00:51:05,131 --> 00:51:09,803
lt may sound weird to you but this is
one of the happiest homes l've ever had.

598
00:51:09,844 --> 00:51:12,347
l know Charlie feels the same way.

599
00:51:14,766 --> 00:51:18,811
Doesn't look like it now
but we really had it together here.

600
00:51:22,313 --> 00:51:24,399
Local artist.

601
00:51:36,909 --> 00:51:38,578
Gracias.

602
00:51:42,748 --> 00:51:45,834
Your son's a pretty popular guy around here.

603
00:51:47,085 --> 00:51:50,588
- The Little Prince?
- That's a great book.

604
00:51:51,673 --> 00:51:55,384
When we first got married,
Charlie read me a chapter everry night.

605
00:51:55,426 --> 00:51:59,263
lt's about this little prince
and he meets a wild fox in the desert,

606
00:51:59,303 --> 00:52:02,932
and little by little, by being verry gentle
and kind and thoughtful,

607
00:52:02,973 --> 00:52:07,478
he tames the fox,
so the fox tells him a secret. Let's see.

608
00:52:09,562 --> 00:52:13,442
''lt's only with the heart
that one can see rightly.

609
00:52:13,483 --> 00:52:16,653
''What is essential is invisible to the eye.''

610
00:52:18,321 --> 00:52:20,740
What is essential?

611
00:52:20,781 --> 00:52:22,866
The stuff you can't see.

612
00:52:28,621 --> 00:52:31,457
This is Charles' handwriting, isn't it?

613
00:52:33,501 --> 00:52:36,920
''Once upon a time,
there was a county so far north

614
00:52:36,962 --> 00:52:39,965
''it was further north than the North Pole.''

615
00:52:42,217 --> 00:52:47,805
ls this part of the same book? No.
Charles...wrote this.

616
00:52:49,056 --> 00:52:51,475
''lt was further north than the Big Dipper.

617
00:52:51,516 --> 00:52:55,978
''lt was even further north than the
Milky Way, and that's pretty far north.''

618
00:52:56,019 --> 00:52:59,398
''Nobody knew its name
except the folks who lived there,

619
00:52:59,440 --> 00:53:03,985
''because the ink in the explorers' pen
froze before they could write it down.''

620
00:53:04,027 --> 00:53:06,821
What does this mean -
''The Sunshine Grabber''?

621
00:53:06,863 --> 00:53:10,533
That's the name of an animated film
Charlie's working on.

622
00:53:10,573 --> 00:53:12,409
This is one of the characters.

623
00:53:13,035 --> 00:53:15,329
Recognise the eyes?

624
00:53:19,456 --> 00:53:24,086
But he seems so innocent,
almost deliberately naive.

625
00:53:26,005 --> 00:53:28,090
ls that so bad?

626
00:53:29,091 --> 00:53:31,551
ls that so good?

627
00:53:31,592 --> 00:53:33,678
You raised him.

628
00:53:38,057 --> 00:53:41,268
- Who is it?
- moman) Soy yo, Beth.

629
00:53:41,309 --> 00:53:43,186
Hello.

630
00:53:46,481 --> 00:53:48,899
Señora Duran. Ed Horman.

631
00:53:48,941 --> 00:53:52,653
This is the lady whose mother
lives across the street.

632
00:53:52,694 --> 00:53:54,780
- Hello.
- Buenos dias.

633
00:53:56,197 --> 00:53:59,325
- El coche está esperando.
- Taxi's waiting.

634
00:54:02,119 --> 00:54:04,204
Aquí, a la derecha.

635
00:54:05,247 --> 00:54:08,750
l was leaving my mother,
who lives across the street.

636
00:54:08,792 --> 00:54:13,796
A taxi came for me just when the soldiers
put your husband in the truck.

637
00:54:14,588 --> 00:54:16,882
Ahora a la izquierda, por favor.

638
00:54:27,807 --> 00:54:31,395
My taxi followed
the same road the truck took.

639
00:54:34,439 --> 00:54:38,818
They drove right into that big door
and went inside the stadium.

640
00:54:38,859 --> 00:54:41,570
- How come you followed them?
- She didn't...

641
00:54:41,612 --> 00:54:45,157
Let her answer.
Why did your taxi follow the truck?

642
00:54:45,198 --> 00:54:47,826
Well, l just live beyond the stadium.

643
00:54:47,867 --> 00:54:52,205
l have to go past here when l come
from the house of my mother.

644
00:54:57,834 --> 00:55:00,253
- l don't believe that!
- Ed, don't.

645
00:55:00,295 --> 00:55:03,965
Don't. They could arrest her
just for talking to us.

646
00:55:10,887 --> 00:55:15,308
Hello, Beth. Mr Horman,
my name's Kate Newman. l'm a reporter.

647
00:55:15,349 --> 00:55:19,812
ls it true you are fed up with the way
the embassy's been handling this

648
00:55:19,853 --> 00:55:22,523
and you're planning your own investigation?

649
00:55:22,563 --> 00:55:25,900
- There's Putnam.
- Er...

650
00:55:25,942 --> 00:55:30,988
l'm not interested in challenging them,
l'm concerned with getting back my son.

651
00:55:31,030 --> 00:55:34,241
- Excuse us, please.
- Beth, get him to talk to me.

652
00:55:34,283 --> 00:55:36,368
- OK.
- OK.

653
00:55:41,998 --> 00:55:44,125
- What happened?
- Shall we sit down?

654
00:55:44,166 --> 00:55:45,834
ls there any news?

655
00:55:45,876 --> 00:55:49,254
We bacMracked
over all our militay leads so far.

656
00:55:49,296 --> 00:55:51,798
They still deny knowledge of his arrest.

657
00:55:51,839 --> 00:55:55,801
We had a fingerprint check made
at all the morgues. Came up negative.

658
00:55:55,842 --> 00:55:59,555
- Do you trust your sources?
- Captain Tower checked them.

659
00:55:59,595 --> 00:56:02,891
- Then l'm sure they're impeccable.
- What we need now

660
00:56:02,933 --> 00:56:05,894
is more background information,
mostly from Beth.

661
00:56:05,934 --> 00:56:08,604
For example, why you were living here.

662
00:56:09,938 --> 00:56:13,609
We were tired of seeing the world
through the New York Times.

663
00:56:13,649 --> 00:56:16,152
- Why this county?
- Of all Latin America,

664
00:56:16,193 --> 00:56:18,905
- this seemed the best.
- Politically?

665
00:56:18,946 --> 00:56:22,491
ln everry way, till your generals took over.

666
00:56:22,532 --> 00:56:24,618
They're not our generals.

667
00:56:24,659 --> 00:56:27,454
Why don't we shift our ground a little here?

668
00:56:27,496 --> 00:56:30,248
- Beth, what was Charles doing?
- Was?

669
00:56:30,289 --> 00:56:33,709
l'm sorry.
What kind of work is Charles doing?

670
00:56:33,751 --> 00:56:38,297
He's working on an animated children's film
and he writes articles.

671
00:56:38,338 --> 00:56:40,424
- Articles for FIN?
- What is FIN?

672
00:56:40,465 --> 00:56:42,467
lt's a left-wing newspaper.

673
00:56:42,509 --> 00:56:46,137
lt is not left-wing.
Besides, he doesn't write for it.

674
00:56:46,179 --> 00:56:49,932
He translates news stories
for such bastions of communism

675
00:56:49,974 --> 00:56:53,018
as the New York Post
and the Wall Street Journal.

676
00:56:53,060 --> 00:56:55,186
- There's another theoy.
- What?

677
00:56:55,227 --> 00:56:58,648
That your son was picked up
by leftists posing as soldiers.

678
00:56:58,689 --> 00:57:03,610
As a matter of fact, there are even people
who think it may have been his idea.

679
00:57:04,694 --> 00:57:06,696
You've gotta be kidding me.

680
00:57:06,737 --> 00:57:11,117
He could've done it to make it look like
the government are arresting Americans.

681
00:57:11,159 --> 00:57:13,285
They are arresting Americans.

682
00:57:13,327 --> 00:57:16,246
Or don't David Holloway
and Frank Teruggi count?!

683
00:57:16,287 --> 00:57:18,373
Shh. Of course they count.

684
00:57:18,415 --> 00:57:21,543
l heard about them
in Washington, Teruggi and...

685
00:57:21,584 --> 00:57:24,712
They're released, right?
We should speak to them.

686
00:57:24,754 --> 00:57:27,047
- We're seeing David tomorrow.
- We are?

687
00:57:27,965 --> 00:57:29,633
ls that my list?

688
00:57:29,674 --> 00:57:33,178
No. These are things
l'd just like you to check on.

689
00:57:35,387 --> 00:57:37,223
Hm.

690
00:57:38,474 --> 00:57:40,643
OK, l'll do my best.

691
00:57:41,726 --> 00:57:44,521
Well, if that's all
l guess we can get back'to work.

692
00:57:44,563 --> 00:57:49,442
Just one moment, please.
To be frank, l know that in these countries,

693
00:57:49,483 --> 00:57:53,070
the embassies have agents
involved with the police

694
00:57:53,111 --> 00:57:56,365
- and militay training...
- This has nothing...

695
00:57:56,405 --> 00:58:00,285
l assume that this case
has something to do with it,

696
00:58:00,326 --> 00:58:02,662
and l don't care how or who runs it,

697
00:58:02,702 --> 00:58:05,539
l just want you to use it
to help find my son.

698
00:58:05,581 --> 00:58:09,084
- l assure you...
- That's all l have to say.

699
00:58:11,586 --> 00:58:15,089
l noticed you were talking
with a reporter before.

700
00:58:15,130 --> 00:58:19,843
lt might be better for the investigation
if you hold off on that for a while.

701
00:58:19,884 --> 00:58:21,970
You know what l mean?

702
00:58:22,012 --> 00:58:24,931
- l'll hold off.
- Good.

703
00:58:26,432 --> 00:58:28,226
Mrs Horman.

704
00:58:28,267 --> 00:58:32,313
- Three, please.
- l can't believe what you said there.

705
00:58:32,353 --> 00:58:36,566
lf you call a spade a spade,
you'll get a favourable response.

706
00:58:36,608 --> 00:58:39,736
- You can also get dead.
- That's your paranoia.

707
00:58:39,777 --> 00:58:42,154
- And, of course, Charles's.
- Ed...

708
00:58:42,195 --> 00:58:45,199
Why didn't you make the list of his friends?

709
00:58:45,239 --> 00:58:47,993
- Are you serious?
- Do l look like l'm joking?

710
00:58:48,033 --> 00:58:53,915
Five minutes after l give that list to Tower,
those friends will probably be arrested.

711
00:58:53,956 --> 00:58:58,877
- Charles knew some dangerous people.
- We're not criminals, Ed!

712
00:58:58,918 --> 00:59:01,505
- Charlie's not a failure.
- l didn't say that.

713
00:59:01,545 --> 00:59:03,590
You always imply it.

